1 agent — AgentCore Runtime, the only thing with an LLM reasoning loop.
3 tools (deterministic, not LLM sub-agents):
Kafka Live Stats → consults Metrics KB for how to build the current matrix
Redshift Stats → consults Insights/Historical KB (which itself does schema→SQL→execute against Aurora/Redshift) for the baseline matrix
Compare/Anomaly → consults Rules KB for thresholds, and is the only one that actually computes anything
Sequencing: Runtime fans out to Kafka Live Stats + Redshift Stats in parallel first, then — only once both return — calls Compare, since Compare needs both matrices before it can do anything.

Kafka Live Stats → calls Metrics KB to get the definition of how to compute the current matrix (which fields, what aggregation) from live data
Redshift Stats → calls Insights/Historical KB (which itself goes schema → SQL → execute against Aurora/Redshift) to get the definition of how to read/compute the baseline matrix
Compare/Anomaly → calls Rules KB to get the actual thresholds/rule logic to apply once it has both matrices
So it's not "one sub-agent talks to the KB on everyone's behalf" — it's three sub-agents, each consulting the specific KB relevant to its own matrix, which is exactly why the official diagram shows three separate KBs (Rules/Metrics/Insights-Historical) rather than one combined cache. That's a real correction to the design, not just a naming tweak.